A stable complex of MCM4, MCM6, and MCM7 associates with MCM2 specifically bound to histone H3. A key component of the pre-replication complex, hexameric MCM2-7 complex is likely involved in formation of replication forks and recruitment of replication factors. MCM2/4/6/7 complex possesses ATP-dependent DNA helicase activity and may initiate replication as a DNA unwinding enzyme. MCM4 phosphorylation by Cyclin/CDK1,2 suppresses helicase activity and chromatin binding, regulating replication. MCM4 is highly phosphorylated in mitotic cells
